Perspectives for Sino-American Relations 2019
NEW YORK – In 2018, the new and increasingly unpredictable dynamics of Chinese-American relations had unsettled much of Asia.
A year ago, US President Donald Trump returned from his particularly pompous "state visit plus" in Beijing, from which China had hoped that Trump's anti-Chinese election campaign rhetoric would finally belong to the past.
Twelve months later, China and the United States are embroiled in a trade war, and the Trump government has replaced the "strategic engagement" of the US in China with "strategic competition".
Furthermore, the US-American, European, and Chinese economies and markets were booming a year ago.
Today, there is great uncertainty on the financial markets, with growth slowing down in China and Europe, and higher interest rates beginning to take effect in America.
The uncertainty about the future development of nuclear talks with North Korea is clouding the picture as well.
So, what are the prospects for relations between the US and China in 2019?
It is likely that there will be an agreement on the reduction of the bilateral trade deficit and on the import decisions that China will make in this regard by March.
Agreement on tariff reductions is also possible by then, although the complexity of the issue could extend the planned timeframe.
Würde ein Zoll nach dem anderen verhandelt, könnte ein Jahr ins Land gehen.
Sollten chinesische Wirtschaftsreformer aber einen drastischeren Ansatz wählen, indem sie sich im Laufe der Zeit zur Abschaffung aller Zölle bekennen und die Amerikaner auffordern, es ihnen gleichzutun, könnte ein schnelleres Resultat vorliegen.
Das würde allerdings chinesischen Handelsbeamten zuwiderlaufen, die seit Jahrzehnten geschult werden, wenig herzuschenken, geschweige denn alles auf einmal.
The reform of the so-called forced technology transfer should be relatively uncomplicated.
Nevertheless, a reform is something different from the way contractual agreements could be implemented in practice, even if there should be no specific provisions for technology transfer.
The protection of intellectual property is, however, extremely problematic.
Previous agreements made under the government of President Barack Obama could be reaffirmed.
However, their enforcement or the judicial approach in cases of violations of intellectual property rights remains a hopeless undertaking.
A possible mechanism could be to submit relevant contracts between Chinese and foreign companies to international arbitration courts with a seat in Singapore or Switzerland that are specifically tasked with enforcing the protection of intellectual property.
Should China raise objections, it could develop its own international arbitration procedure located in China.
For that, however, it would have to appoint qualified foreigners to its arbitration council to strengthen international credibility.
No one trusts Chinese commercial courts.
For its own domestic reform needs, China should move towards completely independent commercial and civil chambers of its court system, even if the criminal chamber continues to be under political control.
The American concerns regarding state subsidies within the framework of China's "Made in China 2025" strategy will hardly be dissipated.
The fact is that all countries allow their domestic technology sectors a certain amount of state support, even if it is highest in China.
Even if we would prescribe a maximum amount of state support for a certain company, it would be hard to enforce.
I am not confident that there will be an agreement in this area.
Perhaps America just needs to knock China out of the game by increasing public investments in research and development in the areas of information technology and biotechnology.
We should also not rule out the possibility that China will offer customs reform to the rest of the international community.
In this way, China could at some point decide to take the drastic step of not only agreeing on customs-free trade with the US, but with all member states of the World Trade Organization.
This would offer China almost an irresistible opportunity to position itself as an advocate of global free trade and check the trend towards protectionism.
In the course of such a turnaround, China could ask the member states of the transpacific free trade agreement TPP to join, in order to surpass the US (which has withdrawn from the free trade agreement as one of its first acts) in the region of Asia-Pacific.
China can be remarkably agile when it discovers a political breach and market opening.
The negotiations would be difficult, but Japan's reservations about China's accession to the TPP have decreased since Prime Minister Shinzo Abe's recent visit to Beijing.
Given the central strategic challenges in the US-China relationship, China is likely to be striving in 2019 to reduce conflicts in its relations with other countries in general foreign and security policy.
In relations with Japan, there is already a certain normalization.
Recent data from the Japanese coast guard indicate a significant reduction in Chinese intrusions into the area of the Senkaku-/Diaoyu Islands in the East China Sea.
China is also trying to ease tensions with the Association of Southeast Asian Nations over the South China Sea through accelerated negotiation of a "code of conduct".
Furthermore, China is likely to have a more relaxed relationship with India after the bilateral summit in Wuhan in April.
And China might begin to moderate its stance towards Taiwan, given the election setback suffered by the Democratic Progressive Party of Taiwanese President Tsai Ing-wen, who advocates independence, in the local and regional elections last month.
This would, of course, radically change if the US were to continue with further significant arms sales to Taiwan, which is likely to happen.
Incidents at sea involving the US in the South China Sea will continue to occur, and the conflict could intensify if the US were to further emphasize its stance on "freedom of navigation" next year.
China will continue to implement its major project "New Silk Road" across all of Eurasia.
However, in China, the initiative has caused less political furor in the past few months.
There are already discussions among Chinese officials about revising certain modalities, following negative reactions to Sri Lanka's handover of the Hambantota port to China and concerns about the long-term financiability of the New Silk Road.
2019 could therefore be hearing triumphant reports on the New Silk Road less frequently.
In addition, China is likely to consolidate and expand its role within the United Nations and existing Bretton Woods institutions, rather than highlighting new institutions of international political action.
It will probably continue to appear as a new advocate of the WHO and maintain its stance on global climate change, as agreed in the Paris Climate Agreement in 2015.
More precise representatives of China's foreign policy establishment believe it is better to concentrate on the existing mechanisms of the global rule-based system, especially if the US consistently shows contempt for them.
While China is trying to stabilize its relations with the US again and reduce tensions in its relations with the other countries, its leadership will probably use the year 2019 to form a well-founded opinion about the future of US policy: the consequences of the Mueller investigation for Trump and his government, and whether a new president in 2020 (or earlier) would change the new US strategy in any way.
Although they have already concluded that the US attitude towards China has undergone a profound change, they are still unsure of what form this change will take and whether a fundamental change in strategy (as opposed to tactical measures) is indicated.
